---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="What is a Stone? UK Weight Unit Explained" description="What is a stone in weight? How to convert stones to kg and lbs, and why the UK still uses this traditional unit." keywords="stone weight, what is a stone, stone to kg, stone to lbs, UK weight unit, stones and pounds, British weight measurement">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Weight</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="What is a Stone? UK Weight Unit Explained" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 7, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>If you have ever spoken to someone from the UK about their weight, you may have heard them say something like "I weigh 11 stone 4." For much of the world, this unit sounds archaic or confusing. Here is everything you need to know about the stone as a unit of weight.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">How Much is a Stone?</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 stone = 14 pounds = 6.35 kg</p>
      </div>
      <p>The stone (abbreviated "st") is a traditional British unit of weight equal to exactly 14 pounds or approximately 6.35 kilograms. It is used almost exclusively in the UK and Ireland for measuring body weight.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Converting Stones to Other Units</h2>
      <p>To convert from stones to other units:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Stones to pounds:</strong> multiply by 14</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Stones to kilograms:</strong> multiply by 6.35</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Pounds to stones:</strong> divide by 14</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Kilograms to stones:</strong> divide by 6.35</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> 12 stone 7 lbs = (12 × 14) + 7 = 175 lbs = 79.4 kg</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Common Body Weights in Stones</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>8 stone = 112 lbs = 50.8 kg</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>10 stone = 140 lbs = 63.5 kg</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>11 stone = 154 lbs = 69.9 kg</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>12 stone = 168 lbs = 76.2 kg</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>13 stone = 182 lbs = 82.6 kg</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>15 stone = 210 lbs = 95.3 kg</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Why Does the UK Still Use Stones?</h2>
      <p>Britain officially adopted the metric system in 1965, but old habits die hard. The stone persists in everyday conversation for several reasons:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Cultural habit</strong> — generations grew up using stones, and parents teach children what they know</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Convenient scale</strong> — whole stone numbers are easier to remember than three-digit pound or kilogram values</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Media reinforcement</strong> — British newspapers and TV still report celebrity weights in stones</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>NHS influence</strong> — while doctors use kg, many GP scales display both</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">History of the Stone</h2>
      <p>The stone dates back to at least the 14th century when it was used for weighing agricultural commodities. Before standardisation, a "stone" varied by region and product — a stone of wool weighed differently from a stone of meat. In 1824, the British Weights and Measures Act fixed it at exactly 14 pounds.</p>

      <p>Today, the stone is not recognised as an official SI unit and is rarely used outside the UK and Ireland. If you are travelling or communicating internationally, converting to kg or lbs will be better understood.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/weight" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Weight Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/weight" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
